# Forked react-native-resource-calendar — Persistent Context

The franchise calendar uses a **locally vendored fork** of `react-native-resource-calendar` v1.1.0. Anything to do with the day-view header (avatars), drag-to-reorder, multi-select filtering, double-tap to enter Workweek, or quick-swap-with-Undo lives across this fork plus a small handful of consumer files. Read this before touching any of those.

> **App-wide gesture convention** (see `gesture-conventions.mdc`): **single tap = primary action, double-tap-and-hold = move, long-press = options.** The calendar's appointment-card drag-init uses **double-tap-and-hold** (the `doubleTapHandledRef` state machine + "doubleTap drag-init" mechanism in `dist/index.js`). The avatar long-press described in this file is an **exception** scoped to the avatar strip — do not generalize it to content objects elsewhere in the app.

## The library is vendored — DO NOT `npm install` upstream

- The dependency line in the root `package.json` is `"react-native-resource-calendar": "file:./vendor/react-native-resource-calendar"`.
- The previous `patch-package` patch (`patches/react-native-resource-calendar+1.1.0.patch`) was deleted; its changes are **already baked into `vendor/react-native-resource-calendar/dist/`**.
- Do not `npm install react-native-resource-calendar@latest`, do not run `patch-package` for it, do not delete the `vendor/` folder. If you need to upgrade, follow the "Updating from upstream" section in `vendor/react-native-resource-calendar/README-FORK.md`.
- The root `tsconfig.json` excludes `vendor/` so the project compiles against the vendored `dist/index.d.ts` (NOT the `vendor/.../src/` files).
- Metro resolves the package via the `react-native` field, which points at `dist/index.js`. **`dist/index.mjs` is intentionally NOT in sync** with the gesture/header changes — only `.js` (and the matching `.d.ts` and `.d.mts`) are kept current.

